119. 3. platalea. This name occurs nowhere else. Pliny H. N. X, 49 40, p. 700 calls the bird platea and says the same of it as Cicero does here. Aristotle H. An. IX, 10 says of επελεκᾶς, that he throws up the muscles which he swallowed alive with the shells closed ; and then as they are dead and the shells are open he takes out the meat and leaves the shells. It is the meat that Cicero here calls en quaesunt esculenta. -What Pliny and Cicero tell of the robbing of the booty from other birds is told by modern naturalists of a sort of mew, the Lestrr'r parasilica or Larus para· silicus-Instead of lu quod ipsa invaderet the Mss. have id quod, evidently an error, because the relative sentence does not serve at all to detine the preceding captum. Comp. Schoem. Opusc. Ac. 111, 337.
